  "articleSummary": "The article argues that modern security breaches no longer require sophisticated malware—they exploit developer workflows, misconfigured CI/CD (e.g., GitHub Actions with movable version tags), and prompt injection in AI agents that treat untrusted content as commands. Key technologies discussed include infostealers like Lumma, poisoned dependencies, fake CAPTCHAs, and AI shell access. The tone is an urgent, analytical warning, using metaphors such as \"credential warehouse with a keyboard\" and \"half-trusted doors\" to frame the developer environment as the primary attack surface. The intended audience is developers and security professionals, with a recurring theme that \"you are the breach\"—emphasizing that user actions (e.g., pasting commands, approving workflows) can be the vector.",
